The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	Jaipur, Dec. 22 (PTI): A court on Monday issued a notice to a member of the erstwhile Jaipur royal family on a police petition seeking cancellation of his bail in a road accident case.          
	Vijit Singh had allegedly hit five girls while driving, killing one of them and injuring four. The court directed Singh to appear before it in person or through his counsel on January 2.                  
	 Varanasi: Three teachers of a college in Mirzamurad were arrested on Monday for allegedly trying to sexually assault a Class XII girl of the institute. The girl, missing since December 12, had left a letter addressed to her father where she accused the three teachers of Arjun Prasad Inter College of sexually exploiting her. She wrote she would commit suicide.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): Mumbai, Hyderabad, Chennai and Calcutta will now have bases of the NSG, the elite counter-terrorism force. Mumbai, Calcutta, Hyderabad and Chennai are the four places that have been identified to establish the new NSG hubs. These hubs will be manned by the existing force of the NSG as of now, J.K. Dutt, the director-general of the force, said after meeting Union home secretary Madhukar Gupta.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): Indias forests have lost at least 110 tigers in the past six years because of poaching and other reasons, according to government data. The figures reveal that the tigers have been unsafe not only in non-protected areas but also inside reserves. This year, 14 tiger deaths were reported till November.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): The Lok Sabha has passed a bill allowing increasing the number of Supreme Court judges from 25 to 30, excluding the Chief Justice of India.                                                                                                                          
